# FireyFastFingers - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a comprehensive typing tester application that tests all symbols on a keyboard, including:
- Words (from a pool of ~400 common words)
- Symbols (all keyboard symbols: `~!@#$%^&*()_+-=[]{}|;:'",.<>?/`)
- Numbers (single digits and sequences)
- Key combinations (Ctrl+A, Ctrl+C, Shift+Enter, etc.)
- Modifier keys (Ctrl, Shift, Alt, Meta/Super)
- Special keys (Enter, Esc, Tab, Backspace, Space, Arrow keys, Caps Lock)

## Technology Stack
- **Runtime**: Bun (use `bun` commands, not Node.js)
- **Frontend**: React 19 with TypeScript
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS 4
- **Server**: Bun.serve() with HTML imports (no Vite)
- **Build**: Bun's built-in bundler

## Bun-Specific Rules

### Commands
- Use `bun <file>` instead of `node <file>` or `ts-node <file>`
- Use `bun test` instead of `jest` or `vitest`
- Use `bun build <file.html|file.ts|file.css>` instead of `webpack` or `esbuild`
- Use `bun install` instead of `npm install` or `yarn install` or `pnpm install`
- Use `bun run <script>` instead of `npm run <script>`
- Use `bunx <package> <command>` instead of `npx <package> <command>`
- Bun automatically loads .env, so don't use dotenv

### APIs
- `Bun.serve()` supports WebSockets, HTTPS, and routes. Don't use `express`.
- `bun:sqlite` for SQLite. Don't use `better-sqlite3`.
- `Bun.redis` for Redis. Don't use `ioredis`.
- `Bun.sql` for Postgres. Don't use `pg` or `postgres.js`.
- `WebSocket` is built-in. Don't use `ws`.
- Prefer `Bun.file` over `node:fs`'s readFile/writeFile
- Bun.$`ls` instead of execa.

### Frontend Development
- Use HTML imports with `Bun.serve()`. Don't use `vite`.
- HTML files can import .tsx, .jsx or .js files directly
- `<link>` tags can point to stylesheets and Bun's CSS bundler will bundle
- Run with `bun --hot ./src/index.ts` for hot reloading

## Project Structure

### Key Files
- `src/index.ts` - Server entry point using Bun.serve()
- `src/index.html` - HTML entry point
- `src/frontend.tsx` - React app entry point
- `src/App.tsx` - Main app component
- `src/components/TypingTest.tsx` - Main typing test component
- `src/hooks/useTypingTest.ts` - Core typing test logic hook
- `src/data/testItemPools.ts` - Test data pools (words, symbols, combos, etc.)
- `src/utils/testGenerator.ts` - Test item generation logic
- `src/utils/keyboardUtils.ts` - Keyboard event handling utilities
- `src/utils/platformUtils.ts` - Platform-specific utilities (Mac vs Windows key display)
- `src/types/test.types.ts` - TypeScript type definitions

### Test Configuration
- Total items per test: 100
- Distribution:
  - 20% words
  - 25% symbols
  - 10% single numbers
  - 10% number sequences
  - 15% key combinations
  - 10% standalone modifiers
  - 10% special keys

### Key Features
- Real-time typing feedback (correct/incorrect)
- Progress tracking with visual progress bar
- Automatic pause on tab switch (visibility API)
- Caps Lock detection and warning
- Platform-aware key display (Cmd vs Ctrl)
- Statistics tracking (WPM, IPM, accuracy, breakdown by type)
- Prevents dangerous browser shortcuts during test

### Component Architecture
- `TypingTest` - Main container component
- `TestControls` - Start test controls
- `TestDisplay` - Current item display with feedback
- `ProgressBar` - Visual progress indicator
- `TestResults` - Results screen with statistics

### State Management
- Uses React hooks (useState, useEffect, useCallback, useRef)
- Test state includes: items, currentIndex, startTime, endTime, results, isActive, isPaused
- Keyboard event listeners managed via useEffect
- Visibility change listener for pause/resume

## Code Style Guidelines

### TypeScript
- Use strict mode (enabled in tsconfig.json)
- Define types in `src/types/` directory
- Use interfaces for object shapes
- Prefer type unions for discriminated unions (e.g., TestItemType)

### React
- Use functional components with hooks
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks
- Use useCallback for event handlers passed to children
- Use useRef for values that don't trigger re-renders

### Keyboard Handling
- Normalize key names using `normalizeKey()` utility
- Prevent default for dangerous shortcuts during active tests
- Track pressed keys in a Set for combo validation
- Handle keydown and keyup events separately
- Validate modifiers on keyup for standalone modifier tests

### Testing
- Use `bun test` for running tests
- Test files should use `import { test, expect } from "bun:test"`

## Development Workflow
1. Start dev server: `bun dev` (runs `bun --hot src/index.ts`)
2. Server runs with HMR enabled in development
3. Console logs from browser echo to server console
4. Build for production: `bun run build`

## Important Notes
- The app prevents dangerous browser shortcuts (Ctrl+W, Ctrl+Q, etc.) during active tests
- Key combinations are validated to ensure exact modifier matches
- Standalone modifiers must be pressed and released alone (no other keys)
- Tab switching automatically pauses the test
- All keyboard symbols from US English keyboard layout are tested



